04828nam a22007095i 9780231553056DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020019034  a97802315530567 a10.7312/subr199322doi  a(DE-B1597)566398  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aQP451b.S82 2021 4aQP451 7aSCI0360002bisacsh04a612.8/82231 aSubramanian, Sushma, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow to Feel :bThe Science and Meaning of Touch /cSushma Subramanian. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 Dull How Our Cultures Lost Touch -- t2 Numb Life Without Touch -- t3 Mushy When Sensation Crosses Into Emotion -- t4 Untethered Will the Body Become Obsolete? -- t5 Softening Overcoming Touch Aversion -- t6 Boundaries Knowing Good Touch from Bad -- t7 Slick How Companies Sell Us Touch -- t8 Haptics Bringing Touch to Our Technology -- t9 Tactful Building Machines That Can Touch Us Back -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe are out of touch. Many people fear that we are trapped inside our screens, becoming less in tune with our bodies and losing our connection to the physical world. But the sense of touch has been undervalued since long before the days of digital isolation. Because of deeply rooted beliefs that favor the cerebral over the corporeal, touch is maligned as dirty or sentimental, in contrast with supposedly more elevated modes of perceiving the world.How to Feel explores the scientific, physical, emotional, and cultural aspects of touch, reconnecting us to what is arguably our most important sense. Sushma Subramanian introduces readers to the scientists whose groundbreaking research is underscoring the role of touch in our lives. Through vivid individual stories—a man who lost his sense of touch in his early twenties, a woman who experiences touch-emotion synesthesia, her own efforts to become less touch averse—Subramanian explains the science of the somatosensory system. She visits labs that are shaping the textures of objects we use every day, from cereal to synthetic fabrics. The book highlights the growing field of haptics, which is trying to incorporate tactile interactions into devices such as phones that touch us back and prosthetic limbs that can feel. How to Feel offers a new appreciation for a vital but misunderstood sense and how we can use it to live more fully in our world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aTouch. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Human Anatomy & Physiology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073907708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2021 Englishz978311075414808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2021z9783110753912oZDB-23-DPM40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/subr1993240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231553056423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231553056/original  a978-3-11-073907-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075414-8  EBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  